<sn><md>### Installing Aria2

**Ubuntu / Debian**

```bash
sudo apt update
sudo apt install aria2
```

Verify installation:

```bash
aria2c --version
```
</md></sn><sn><md>### Basic Usage

Download a File

```bash
aria2c URL
```

Example:

```bash
aria2c https://example.com/file.zip
```
</md></sn><sn><md>#### Saving Files with Custom Names

```bash
aria2c -o myfile.zip URL
```

Example:

```bash
aria2c -o ubuntu.iso https://example.com/download.iso
```
</md></sn><sn><md>### Download to a Specific Directory

```bash
aria2c -d ~/Downloads URL
```

Example:

```bash
aria2c -d ~/Downloads/Linux ubuntu.iso
```

</md></sn><sn><md>#### Accelerating Downloads

One of Aria2's most powerful features is segmented downloading.

## Use Multiple Connections

```bash
aria2c -x 16 -s 16 URL
```

Options:

| Option | Description                    |
| ------ | ------------------------------ |
| -x     | Maximum connections per server |
| -s     | Number of download segments    |

Example:

```bash
aria2c -x 16 -s 16 https://example.com/bigfile.iso
```
</md></sn><sn><md>#### Resume Interrupted Downloads

```bash
aria2c -c URL
```

Example:

```bash
aria2c -c https://example.com/file.zip
```

The download continues from where it stopped.

</md></sn><sn><md>### Limiting Download Speed

**Limit to 1 MB/s**

```bash
aria2c --max-download-limit=1M URL
```

**Limit to 500 KB/s**

```bash
aria2c --max-download-limit=500K URL
```

</md></sn><sn><md>### Download Multiple Files

Create a file:

```text
urls.txt
```

Example:

```text
https://example.com/file1.zip
https://example.com/file2.zip
https://example.com/file3.zip
```

Download:

```bash
aria2c -i urls.txt
```
</md></sn><sn><md>### Parallel Downloads

Download multiple files simultaneously:

```bash
aria2c -i urls.txt -j 5
```

Option:

```text
-j = Number of concurrent downloads
```
</md></sn><sn><md>### Downloading Torrents

**Torrent File**

```bash
aria2c file.torrent
```

**Magnet Link**

```bash
aria2c "magnet:?xt=urn:btih:..."
```
</md></sn><sn><md>#### Downloading Linux ISOs

Example:

```bash
aria2c -x 16 -s 16 \
https://releases.ubuntu.com/ubuntu.iso
```

This often downloads faster than a browser.

</md></sn><sn><md>#### Using Metalink Files

Metalink provides multiple mirrors and checksums.

```bash
aria2c file.metalink
```

Benefits:

* Automatic mirror selection
* Integrity verification
* Faster downloads
</md></sn><sn><md>#### Downloading with Authentication

**Username and Password**

```bash
aria2c \
--http-user=username \
--http-passwd=password \
URL
```

**Basic Authentication URL**

```bash
aria2c https://user:password@example.com/file.zip
```

</md></sn><sn><md>#### Using Cookies

```bash
aria2c --load-cookies=cookies.txt URL
```

Useful for:

* Private downloads
* Logged-in websites
* Session-based access

</md></sn><sn><md>#### Setting User-Agent

Some websites block unknown download tools.

```bash
aria2c \
--user-agent="Mozilla/5.0" \
URL
```

</md></sn><sn><md>#### Verifying Checksums

**SHA256**

```bash
aria2c \
--checksum=sha-256=HASH_VALUE \
URL
```

Example:

```bash
aria2c \
--checksum=sha-256=abc123... \
ubuntu.iso
```

Aria2 verifies file integrity automatically.
</md></sn><sn><md>### RPC Server Mode

Aria2 can run as a background download server.

Start RPC:

```bash
aria2c \
--enable-rpc \
--rpc-listen-all=true \
--rpc-allow-origin-all
```

Useful for:

* Remote management
* Web interfaces
* Automation scripts

</md></sn><sn><md>#### Running in Background

```bash
nohup aria2c URL &amp;
```

or

```bash
screen -S download
aria2c URL
```
</md></sn><sn><md>### Configuration File

Create:

```bash
mkdir -p ~/.config/aria2
nano ~/.config/aria2/aria2.conf
```

Example:

```text
continue=true
max-connection-per-server=16
split=16
min-split-size=1M
max-concurrent-downloads=5
check-certificate=true
```

Now every download automatically uses these settings.
</md></sn><sn><md>### Useful Keyboard Shortcuts

While Aria2 is running:

```text
Ctrl + C    Stop download
Ctrl + Z    Suspend process
fg          Resume suspended process
```
</md></sn><sn><md>#### Troubleshooting

**SSL Certificate Error**

Ignore certificate verification:

```bash
aria2c --check-certificate=false URL
```

Use only when necessary.


**Connection Timeout**

Increase timeout:

```bash
aria2c --timeout=120 URL
```


**Too Many Connections**

Reduce:

```bash
aria2c -x 4 -s 4 URL
```

Some servers block excessive connections.

</md></sn><sn><md>#### Conclusion

Aria2 is one of the fastest and most versatile download managers available for Linux. Its support for segmented downloads, torrents, magnet links, Metalink files, authentication, and remote control makes it an excellent choice for power users. When properly configured, Aria2 can significantly outperform traditional browser downloads and many other command-line download tools.
</md></sn>